9:
Yes, the leader of the Serpent
Research team, in fact...
14:
It's impossible to not feel some
responsibility.
17:
Rather, the academy is grateful if
anything, since this person was
used as a decoy to draw out a spy.
21:
Did the academy know about
Deneb?
26:
It seems that, more or less, they
were aware they were being probed
by the Farlands.
35:
I have more to say about this, but
this isn't the time.
38:
Hmm... From what I've heard, it
sounds more like a case of
somebody running from home.
44:
Perhaps, if the place he went
missing in wasn't the Kaleidoscope.
Besides, he has his own account of
things to share.
48:
Was this written by that student? It
seems like he approaches his work
in much the same way as I...
51: Yes, but take a look at the last page.
55: He dreamed of a sleeping dragon.
61:
The sky above the academy
twinkled with a strange light. That
was probably the bottom of the
Kaleidoscope—
70:
Yes. I've asked the Guild Knights for
help as well, but with our similar
fields, I imagined you could help me
track this person down.
75:
Things would be easier if we could
just apprehend that wrinkly Dark
Mage, but you two have similar skill
sets, no?
80:
...I'd rather you didn't think of us as
being similar.
84:
But at any rate, I understand. Allow
me to be of service.
87:
Luciada. Your voice surely reached
the people.
90:
I feel like I've learned a lesson from
my own student. Now allow me to
live up to the trust you've given me.
95: All right. Thank you, Mr. Liam!
102:
This spell... Yes... And this one! Aha...
AhaHAHAHA!
103:
N-no! Damn it, DAMN IT! That doesn't
make sense! Why is this—
106: Do you intend to press on?
112: ...You... I saw you at the Magia Fest...
115:
Liam Ilde. Mage. I've come to help
you.
118: You can see what I'm seeing, right?
120:
You're in shock. Your perception of
reality is off.
123:
Y-yeah! Everything's completely
crazy! There's no WAY magic like this
should work!
124:
And yet... It's working... And the
deeper I go into the Kaleidoscope,
the more powerful it becomes!
127:
Such fluctuations in the
Kaleidoscope are common to begin
with. We need to leave—
130:
The dragon... it has me! D-dad... HELP
ME, DAD!
140:
Calm down and come this way! The
real world is just out here with me!
143:
This isn't working!
No, he just needs to see something
that defines his own reality!
147:
Listen to me! Remember what
inspired you to become a mage!
151:
Something led you down this path!
What made you desire to seek the
truth?
153:
There's SOMETHING you wanted, so
tell me what it is! Tell me how your
path began!
159:
So I... Could stand, proud... Before my
father... as a mage!
163:
Yes... THAT is your reality! Take hold
and don't let go!
166:
As long as you have that, you won't
melt away!
172:
So you're the one causing all the
trouble. Sorry, but this is where it
ends for you!
175: Take form and defeat my foes!
186:
I feel... normal again. But just a
moment ago, I-I felt...
190: Never forget that sense of fright.
193:
The less you feel that sensation, the
more vulnerable you will be to
wishful thinking—and that isn't fitting
for a researcher.
195:
Yet we must not be paralyzed by our
fear of the darkness, either. Our path
always lies ahead of us.
197:
Nobody is perfect, and we all get
lost from time to time.
200:
B-but... I've caused a lot of trouble
for you and the academy...
202:
Failure and mistakes are themselves
key to uncovering the truth. This is
what it means to walk in the
darkness.
204:
If we never forget why we pursue
truth in the first place, we can
always return to where we were
before.
207:
Can I ask you what your own
motivations are, Liam?
210:
I... simply desired to do something
about things that were outside of
my control.
213:
Such a thing is common enough
among mages, don't you think?
216:
By the way. Do you intend to
become my apprentice?
221:
I got a chance to read your
academic writings. I found it very
interesting.
223:
Also, I wonder if what you just
experienced had something to do
with that bit of serpent tissue you
had in your possession...
226:
U-uh... Let's talk about it at the
academy later! I don't want to
disappoint my new mento—uh, I
mean, my dad...
228:
Hmm, all right, then. I will stop by
your laboratory at a later date.
